\begin_layout Section*
Regressions on Consumer Expenditure Survey
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors consider a black-dummy and hispanic-dummy in regression of visible
 consumption against demographic, time, permanent income and household character
isitcs.
 The hispanic dummy is inferred by the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

horref1
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 variable in CEX data - which is recorded side-by-side with the race variable.
 This means that housholds/individuals can associate with either white or
 black while recording their ethnicity.
 Only about 1489 out of 22980 households surveyed in years 2004, 2009 and
 2014, for example, associate with neither white nor black.
 If that criterion is relaxed (i.e.
 if anyhone reporting the horref1 variable is considered hispanic for the
 study) the number of hispanics in the survey almost doubles.
 Starting with no controls(I)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+hispanic_dummy)
\end_layout

\end_inset

 (with black-dummy and hispanic-dummy), the coefficients for coloured and
 black are negative (i.e.
 black and hispanic social groups spend less on visible consumption than
 the white population).
 These coefficients flip signs after adding income controls(II)
\begin_inset Foot
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\family typewriter
lm(lnvis~black_dummy+coloured_dummy+ lninc+incpsv+cbinc) 
\family default
- where lninc is log(income), incpsv is dummy for positive income and cbinc
 is income-cubinc.
\end_layout

\end_inset

 .
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The authors report problems with the quality of income data in the survey
 and point out the log-expenditure is a better candidate for the study.
