 families.
 Further, the frequency of purchases gets lower as the quantity of bulk
 purchases increase.
 We can probably estimate the number of rooms as a proxy of storage space
 - but store and consume is itself a consumption pattern.
 This may happen more when the closest market is distant from the household.
 The data for distance from market (or the cost from( public transport)
 is quite sparse (a lot of NAs).
 The NAs could be because the market as described in the survey is never
 visited (or it doesn't exist in the immediate region).
 We would assume that the habit of stocking is uniform throughout the country
 - which might be sweeping assumption - but since we do take region into
 account - we should be able to account regional differences or household
